TY  - JOUR
T1  - Generation Cohorts and Personal Values: A Comparison of China and the United States
AU  - Egri, Carolyn P.
AU  - Ralston, David A.
Y1  - 2004/04/01
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/orsc.1030.0048
DO  - 10.1287/orsc.1030.0048
T2  - Organization Science
JF  - Organization Science
JO  - Organization Science
SP  - 210
EP  - 220
VL  - 15
IS  - 2
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This study investigated the generation cohort value orientations of 774 Chinese and 784 U.S. managers and professionals. The three Chinese generations (Consolidation, Cultural Revolution, Social Reform) since the establishment of Communist China were significantly more open to change and self-enhancement but less conservative and self-transcendent than the Republican Era generation. The value orientations of U.S. generations (Generation X, Baby Boomer, Silent generation) followed an age-related pattern with the exception of self-transcendence values. The least similar value orientations were between Chinese and U.S. generations that had grown up during Communist China's closed-door policy. The more entrepreneurial value orientations of the most recent Chinese generations appear to be compatible with organizational changes currently under way in China's state-owned sector.
AB  - This study investigated the generation cohort value orientations of 774 Chinese and 784 U.S. managers and professionals. The three Chinese generations (Consolidation, Cultural Revolution, Social Reform) since the establishment of Communist China were significantly more open to change and self-enhancement but less conservative and self-transcendent than the Republican Era generation. The value orientations of U.S. generations (Generation X, Baby Boomer, Silent generation) followed an age-related pattern with the exception of self-transcendence values. The least similar value orientations were between Chinese and U.S. generations that had grown up during Communist China's closed-door policy. The more entrepreneurial value orientations of the most recent Chinese generations appear to be compatible with organizational changes currently under way in China's state-owned sector.
